From: hpa@ahab.eecs.nwu.edu (H. Peter Anvin N9ITP)
Subject: Re: how fast is linux?
Reply-To: hpa@nwu.edu (H. Peter Anvin)
Date: Sat, 20 Nov 1993 11:43:15 GMT

In article <1993Nov19.183401.20344@rosevax.rosemount.com> of
comp.os.linux.misc, grante@hydro.rosemount.com (Grant Edwards) writes:
> 
> OTOH, compared to anything else on a 386 machine like I've got, Linux
> flies.  Especially when you consider the price.  With an accellerated
> SVGA board and a 486 it must be great.
>

It is.  I can myself attest to that.

Current Linux setup:

Machine A:

   486DX2-66 VLB
   16 Mb RAM with 256K cache
   400 Mb IDE hard disk (16 Mb /, 340 Mb /usr and 47 Mb swap for Linux)
   ATI Ultra Pro VLB video board (1 Mb)
   SMC Elite Combo Ethernet board

Machine B:

   486DX-33 ISA
   16 Mb RAM with 64K cache
   200 Mb IDE hard disk (30 Mb / and 16 Mb swap for Linux)
   ATI Ultra video board
   SMC Elite Combo Ethernet board

Machine B mounts /usr via NFS from machine A.  Machine A provides a
lot of network services, such as distributing the linux-activistists
mailing list via NNTP (using INN) and serving as a home for several
mailing lists, some rather large.

They really rock... each machine cost about $3K when we got them (A
early this year, B early last year), and they are being put to heavy
use every day.  Machine A, in fact, was bought specifically to run
Linux.  (The reason it has 47 Mb swap is that I initially thought I'd
better leave a DOS partition on the system... it doesn't use more than
maybe 12 Mb of it at the most).

> 
> Is it time to start reminiscing about 8 users an 11/03 runnin V7 with
> 256K words of RAM and a 40M disk?  (And we _liked_ it!)
> 

Another machine I run is a 386DX-16 with 3 Mb expansion bus RAM and a
40 Mb MFM HD running Linux.  It works, and it usable, but occationally
it locks up due, apparently, to RAM problems.  I will hopefully get a
40 MHz MB with 4-8 Mb really soon now... :-)

        /hpa
