From: rstevew@armory.com (Richard Steven Walz)
Crossposted-To: comp.sys.ibm.pc.hardware,sci.electronics
Subject: Re: Tape Backups H/W
Date: 20 Nov 93 10:20:09 GMT

In article <1993Nov16.230047.11866@cse.dnd.ca>,
Thomas Monk <tmonk@cse.dnd.ca> wrote:
>Hi,
>
>       I was wondering if anybody would know if there is a piece
>of hardware for a PC that can be used for accessing a VCR, for tape
>back ups.
>       Or if someone would know where I could find a schematic for
>building one?
>
>       The best possible device would be one that attached to either
>a parallel or serial port.
>
>               Thanks for your help,
>                       Tom Monk.
=============================================
I have a plug-in card that uses my VCR as a backup tape drive. It writes
the data three times, and it requires the use of good quality tape at the
highest tape speed SP, but it has only a bit failure rate of one hard error
per 100 million MEGABytes!! It was made by autofax, which used to be in
Scotts Valley, CA, and it is called the "Imager". It operates either on the
entire disk or on selected subdirectories recursively. I can get about
80 MB per 120 minute tape. Not fantastic, but I traded some junk for it.
I don't use it often, not as often as floppies, and I have turned to
backing up software packages in installed form rather than just copying
file after file. But it did safe my ass once, so it was well worth it.
There may be better ones on the market now, for all I know. But with so
many good and fairly cheap tape drives out there now, my next tape backup
would not be VCR! The company is no defunct, sorry.
-Steve Walz   rstevew@armory.com


